{
  "doc_id": "48680",
  "text": "All three translocases have been found to associate with the replication fork; however, how they do it is distinct. SMA RCAL1 travels with the replication fork and becomes further enriched following replication stress through interaction with RPA [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . SMA RCAL1's interaction with RPA is important for providing substrate specificity to promote replication fork reversal and prevent activity during normal DNA replication [CITATION_8] . ATR phosphorylation of S652 of RPA-bound SMA RCAL1 has been shown to be important for regulating its activity at the replication fork [CITATION_9] .",
